# ERP Frontend Reference Rule

Use these defaults when implementing features in this repo.

Tech baseline in this project:
- React 19 + Vite
- React Router
- CSS variables/theme system in `src/styles`
- Context-based domain state (primary, current production pattern)
- React Query + API helpers available for new backend-connected features

## Architecture and Structure
- Respect this folder ownership model:
  - `src/components/*`: feature and layout UI
  - `src/pages/*`: route-level pages (landing/auth/onboarding/employee/auditor)
  - `src/routes/appRoutes.jsx`: canonical route tree
  - `src/context/*`: domain state providers (Accounting, HR, Inventory, Audit, etc.)
  - `src/api/*`: HTTP client and request helpers
  - `src/hooks/*`: custom data hooks (`useCustomQuery`, `useCustomPost`, etc.)
  - `src/services/*`: auth/token/session helpers
  - `src/core/*`: cross-feature primitives (`Pagination`, `Spinner`, `ScrollToTop`)
  - `src/utils/*`: formatting/export/error helpers
  - `src/styles/*`: global theme variables and base styles
- Prefer using existing shared utilities/hooks before introducing new abstractions.
- Keep module-specific logic inside the owning module folder; promote to shared only when reused by 2+ modules.

## Current Data Layer Reality (Important)
- The current app is primarily context-driven with in-memory/mock domain data.
- Do not assume every feature already uses API + React Query.
- When editing existing modules:
  - If module already depends on context providers, keep compatibility.
  - If introducing API-driven flow, isolate it and avoid breaking current context behavior.
- For new backend-connected features, use:
  - `src/hooks/useQuery.js` (`useCustomQuery`) for reads
  - `src/hooks/useMutation.js` (`useCustomPost`, `useCustomPatch`, `useCustomRemove`) for writes
  - `src/services/auth.js` for auth/token/session and tenant-domain helpers
- Do not call `get/post/patch/remove` directly inside pages/components when a custom hook can be used.
- If adding API flow in context providers, wrap requests with `useCustomQuery`/`useCustomPost` style hooks.

## Forms + API Standard (Project Default)
- For forms that submit to APIs, use `react-hook-form` as the default form state/validation approach.
- Prefer `Controller` with shared input components when they do not expose `ref` forwarding.
- Avoid `useState` for API form fields and submission error state in pages/components; use `react-hook-form` state (`errors`, `setError`, `clearErrors`, etc.).
- Combine `react-hook-form` with React Query custom hooks:
  - Submit with `useCustomPost` / `useCustomPatch` / `useCustomRemove`
  - Read option lists/details with `useCustomQuery`
- Keep transport layer on axios through `src/api/index.js`; UI layers should consume hooks, not axios directly.

## Routing and Navigation Rules
- Treat `src/routes/appRoutes.jsx` as the source of truth for route structure.
- Keep public/auth entry locking behavior consistent:
  - Authenticated users must not access `/landing`, `/auth/signin`, or `/auth/signup`
  - Redirect authenticated users from those public routes to their role dashboard (`/admin/dashboard` or `/employee/dashboard`)
  - Keep `/` as the app entry that routes authenticated users to dashboard and unauthenticated users to `/landing`
  - Protect `/admin/*` so unauthenticated users are redirected to `/auth/signin`
- Keep role/layout boundaries intact:
  - `/admin/*` under `AdminLayout`
  - `/employee/*` under `EmployeeLayout`
  - Auditor routes under `/auditor/*`
- When adding a module/section:
  - Add route entries in `appRoutes.jsx`
  - Add matching sidebar/navigation entry when appropriate
  - Verify route path naming stays consistent with existing conventions
- Keep wildcard redirect behavior stable unless explicitly requested.

## ERP UI Conventions
- Use the standard module page flow:
  1) header/title/actions
  2) filters/search row
  3) table or list
  4) modal(s) for add/edit/confirm
- Typography:
  - Buttons: `font-medium`
  - Inputs/selects/textarea: `font-normal`
  - Labels: `font-medium`
- Interaction:
  - Clickable controls must include `cursor-pointer`
  - Keep row hover/action affordances consistent
- Tables:
  - Keep horizontal safety (`overflow-x-auto` or equivalent)
  - Preserve clear header/body visual separation
- Modal behavior:
  - Keep overlay + focus-safe layout patterns consistent with existing app
  - Include clear cancel/submit actions
- User feedback toasts:
  - For user-triggered actions (submit/save/create/update/delete/login/logout), show a suitable toast for both success and failure outcomes.
  - Use `sonner` (already mounted in `App.jsx`) for toast notifications.
  - Keep toast styling compatible with theme tokens (`var(--color-*)`), and avoid inline form-level backend error blocks when a toast is more suitable.
  - Prefer concise action-focused messages (what happened and what user can do next when relevant).

## Responsive and Theme Rules
- Preserve mobile-first behavior in app shell.
- Do not regress sidebar/navbar behavior on small screens.
- Maintain compatibility with the CSS variable theme system:
  - Use `var(--color-*)` tokens from `src/styles/variables.css`
  - Respect `[data-theme="dark"]` behavior and existing transitions
- Avoid hardcoding colors when an existing token exists.

## Naming and Imports
- Components: PascalCase filenames and exports.
- Hooks/utils: camelCase.
- Use `@/` alias imports over long relative paths.
- Keep route/query keys and state names explicit and stable (`isLoading`, `isOpen`, `currentPage`, etc.).

## Feature Implementation Checklist (Default)
- Add/adjust UI in the owning module folder.
- Reuse shared core/util hooks where possible.
- Wire routes/navigation if feature is route-visible.
- Handle loading, empty, and error states.
- Keep Arabic/RTL-friendly layouts stable where already present.
- Validate both desktop and mobile layout behavior.

## Quality and Safety
- Make minimal, targeted edits that match current style and patterns.
- Do not break existing flows in navbar/sidebar, auth, or role-specific routing.
- Do not silently refactor large modules unless requested.
- Preserve backward compatibility for context consumers when introducing new hooks/services.
- After significant changes:
  - run `pnpm lint`
  - fix newly introduced issues
  - verify the affected screen in dev mode
